<p><i>While the Criminal and Procedural Code of 
Uzbekistan is the main document which 
regulates criminal proceedings, it does not 
contain any direct prohibition on the use of 
evidence extorted under torture. Article 3 of the 
Resolution of the Plenary of the Supreme Court 
&#8220;On the application of certain norms of 
criminal and procedural legislation in respect 
of the admission of proof&#8221; dated 24 September 
2004, prohibits the use of evidence obtained 
illegally. The Resolution of the Plenary of the 
Supreme Court No 17 of 2003 also states that 
evidence received by means of torture, force, 
threat, deceit or any other cruel and degrading 
human dignity treatment, and other illegal 
means in violation of the rights of the suspect, 
can not be presented as the basis for the 
accusation. Moreover, in accordance with this 
Regulation, the investigator, prosecutor and 
judge should ask a person coming from a pre-
trial prison or detention centre how he/she was 
treated there. Each complaint of torture from a </i></p>

